Why 28√ó28 with heavy augmentation?
Three versions of this model were built. Here's why each upgrade mattered.
‚ùå Problem

Thick drawn strokes crush all structural features into 64 pixels. The crossbar of a 4 and angle of a 7 become identical blobs.

‚úÖ Best
28√ó28 + Augmentation
784 features
CV Accuracy95.0%
Draw accuracyStrong
4 vs 7Clearly distinct
Fine grid preserves strokes and structural features. Augmentation trains on 27√ó more diverse handwriting styles.
The core insight: The problem wasn't model architecture ‚Äî it was the input representation. When you draw a "4" on screen, your stroke is maybe 180√ó180 pixels. Squeezing that into 8√ó8 = 64 pixels destroys the crossbar that makes a 4 look different from a 7. At 28√ó28 = 784 pixels, the same stroke preserves the horizontal bar, the open top, and the diagonal ‚Äî the features the network actually needs.

Why 27√ó augmentation? The dataset only has 1,797 real samples. We added rotations (¬±15¬∞), thickness variations (Gaussian blur), pixel shifts, and noise ‚Äî growing to 48,500+ samples. This teaches the model that a "4" is still a "4" whether it's slightly tilted, thicker, or shifted ‚Äî matching how real people write.
